That the old Scholastics made little or no progress in scientific discovery proves nothing, Aristotle, the greatest of logicians, was no less great in the sciences of observation and experiment. They did not care for those fields of knowledge, others, to them far more important, absorbed their attention: that accounts for all. But the proof that this view of Induction is the right one would be foreign to the scope of the present Introduction. Wyclif thought as all Schoolmen thought at that time, and there are reasons to believe that they were, and that he was, right.
